Mosque in Temecula wins approval of the planning committee 
The construction of a mosque in Temecula found the unanimous promise of the local planning committee after a five hour, often heated public hearing. 
Critics reproached the project to support both the terrorism and traffic jams. 
However according to a statement of the commission of the Wednesday evening, the new religion center corresponds to the local regulations and an aesthetic eye appeal will become. 
"The project is supported by many good people - of Christians, Jews, Bahais, and many others," declared Hadi Nael, chairpersons' of the Islamic center of Temecula Valley on Thursday tomorrow. 
"As an American that makes me proud." 
It shows, that there is justice." 
"There are only few opponents," he still added. 
"You are only very much loud." 
"In this valley wonderful people live." 
The meeting began at 18:00 and the discussions for and against the construction of the center almost lasted until midnight at which the voices were quite evenly distributed on both pages according to Press-Enterprise. 
The debate kept on being led on the web page of the newspaper. 
"There is not any America anymore," a comment said. 
"It is another planet of the monkeys, and the Statue of Liberty lies in a dead way in the sand." 
"America is at the end." 
Planned Islamic Centers led to protests also in other parts of the country, e.g. near Ground Zero, the scene of the terrorist attacks on the town of New York on 11th September 2001. 
In the Temecula Valley imam Mahmoud Harmoush called for nonviolence. 
His municipality with approx. 135 families lives for years peacefully in the Riverside County. However they wanted a larger and better to locating, as the warehouse that they rented together with a manufacturer for water filter installations. 
The new one, approx. 2.300 m2 big mosque in the mediterranean style is supposed to have two minarets and become about 13 m high. 
They is supposed to arise on that approx. 17.500 m2 large plot at the Nicolas Road near the Chaparral High School. 
Opponents can still make objection to the project with the town council. 
